commit.message:
Add Data.Constraint.Char

For now, this module only provides `charToNat` and `natToChar` operations, but
we may include more operations in the future.

Fixes #117.

Implement Data.Constraint.{Nat,Symbol}'s magic using withKnown{Nat,Symbol} when possible

This reduces the amount of code that has to be `unsafeCoerce`d down to just the
`unsafeSNat` and `unsafeSSymbol` functions, which I have added to
`Data.Constraint.Unsafe`. (If https://gitlab.haskell.org/ghc/ghc/-/issues/23478
were implemented, then we could do away with even those uses of
`unsafeCoerce`.)

Fixes #114.

Move axiom to Data.Constraint.Unsafe, name it unsafeAxiom

The `axiom` definition was redundantly defined twice, once in
`Data.Constraint.Nat` and once more in `Data.Constraint.Symbol`. This patch
replaces these definitions with a single definition in
`Data.Constraint.Unsafe`. Because `Data.Constraint.Unsafe` is exported, I
renamed `axiom` to `unsafeAxiom` to reflect the existing naming conventions
used in `Data.Constraint.Unsafe`.
add hlint config and squelch eta reduction warning

Bump CI to ubuntu-20.04 and GHCs 9.6.1 9.4.4 9.2.7

ubuntu-18.04 has reached EOL

Also: fix outdated git repo link in .cabal file.

Use PolyKinds instead of TypeInType

After GHC 8.6, `TypeInType`'s functionality was made a part of the `DataKinds`
and `PolyKinds` extensions. Moreover, GHC 9.6 gives a deprecation warning when
using `TypeInType`, so we now have an extra incentive to only enable
`TypeInType` where absolutely necessary.

Remove instances for `ErrorT` and `ListT` (fixes #110) (#111)

* Remove instances for ErrorT (#110) for mtl-2.3 and transformers-6.0

* Remove instances for ListT (#110) for mtl-2.3 and transformers-6.0

* Re #110: Bump upper bounds of mtl and transformers; enable deprecation warnings

commit.message:
Generalize the type of axiom

This allows `constraints` to build with GHC HEAD, where the `(<=)` type is no
longer defined directly in terms of `(~)`. See
https://gitlab.haskell.org/ghc/ghc/-/merge_requests/6066.

Allow building with GHC 9.2

See https://gitlab.haskell.org/ghc/ghc/-/wikis/migration/9.2#changes-to-the-and-type-families
for more details on why these changes are needed.
